[1
Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 12:57:47 +0700 (GMT+0700)
From: Henry Wilde MD <wilde@md2.md.chula.ac.th>

PIG TRANSPLANTS
There are now thousands of people walking around with pig heart valves. I
have never heard of any "mad cow disease" or other veterinary malady
related to pig valves. Suggest the author of this note to ProMED-mail do a
Medline of pig valves and check with commercial manufacturers as well. It
might be interesting to do long term follow ups on some of these patients.
I have a friend who has an aortic one that has been working without fail
for at least 15 years. He is well.
--
Henry Wilde
e-mail: wilde@md2.md.chula.ac.th
AND
Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 01:53:09 -0500
From: Alex C. Tselis <atselis@med.wayne.edu>

Bioprosthetic valves have been transplanted from pigs into human hearts for
many years. I don't recall that there has been any outbreak of unusual
viral diseases among human recipients of pig valves. I don't know the
statistics, but presumably one can put an upper bound on the risk of such
an infection by looking into this. Has such a calculation been done?
--
Alex Tselis
e-mail: atselis@med.wayne.edu
[Not that I have read up on the subject, but I believe that these
replacement porcine heart valves were/are recovered from commercially
reared pigs at slaughter. Maybe someone can enlighten me on that specific
point. - Mod.MHJ
***
[2
Date: Mon, 23 Nov 1998 05:38:37 PST
From: Rick Huneke <rickhuneke@hotmail.com>

A organ transplanted from a pig to a human could theoretically be affected
by a swine pathogen if the organism is able to access the organ. For the
pathogen to access the organ, it must be able to invade the new host. I
would suspect that specific receptors are necessary for a virus to invade
the host. If a human does not possess these receptors in the respiratory or
gastrointestinal tracts, it is unlikely that the swine virus could reach
and affect a transplanted swine liver.
In any case, I would not recommend a swine xenograft patient to continue a
job as a hog farmer.
--
Richard Huneke DVM MPH
Senior Research Veterinarian
DuPont Pharmaceuticals Company
