[3

Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 23:04:24 -0600
From: Richard Kennerly <kennerly@unt.edu>

My concern with xenotransplantation in terms of medical risks are the
possibility of prion transmission. I believe most of the obvious risks
would be covered, but prion diseases could pose an unevaluated risk. It is
my understanding that in swine it takes 8 years or more for BSE type
illness to be evident, long after they would be killed for transplantation
(or food).
>From incidents with CJD organ donors we know it can be transmitted via
organ transplantation in humans. I am concerned many patients could die
from iatrogenic CJD type illness before this risk is recognized and addressed.
--
Richard Kennerly
e-mail: kennerly@unt.edu
[To date a natural TSE of swine has yet to be identified, though logic
would suggest that all species have them. The only cases I know of were
from experimental intracranial exposures. Added to which commercial pigs do
not live long enough to show the disease. Most pigs are killed between 6 &
9 months and it is the very exceptional sow that goes over three years. One
would expect donor pigs to follow a similar harvesting pattern. The porcine
prion risk would thus appear to be slight, and if special donor colonies
are being used, as near zero as one can get. - Mod.MHJ
............................................mhj/es
